02:37.171 --> 02:38.871
<i>Some of
the most common pathways</i>

02:38.873 --> 02:41.375
<i>of energy production
in microorganisms,</i>

02:41.377 --> 02:43.744
<i>who live along the
hydrothermal vents,</i>

02:43.746 --> 02:47.347
<i>are oxidation or reduction
of sulfur compounds.</i>

02:47.349 --> 02:49.181
<i>The most common electron donor</i>

02:49.183 --> 02:51.450
<i>along the vents is
hydrogen sulfide,</i>

02:51.452 --> 02:54.420
<i>making oxidation
of sulfur-containing compounds</i>

02:54.422 --> 02:57.193
<i>the base of the food
web in this environment.</i>

02:57.392 --> 03:00.160
<i>The microorganisms
capable of oxidizing</i>

03:00.162 --> 03:02.294
<i>or reducing sulfur compounds</i>

03:02.296 --> 03:04.264
<i>show amazing diversity.</i>

03:04.266 --> 03:09.703
<i>Over 161 gram-negative
sulfur-oxidizing bacteria species</i>

03:09.705 --> 03:13.096
<i>have been found to inhabit
the hydrothermal vents.</i>

03:13.098 --> 03:17.577
<i>Bacteria in this environment are often
thought of as all being autotrophs,</i>

03:17.579 --> 03:20.614
<i>but of these 161 species,</i>

03:20.616 --> 03:24.420
<i>over 97% are also capable
of heterotrophic growth.</i>

03:24.686 --> 03:28.221
<i>In addition, 37% perform
fermentation.</i>

03:28.223 --> 03:31.490
<i>Furthermore, the sulfate
reducers known to be present,</i>

03:31.492 --> 03:36.031
<i>include at least nine different
genera, including gram-negative...</i>

03:36.297 --> 03:37.766
Yeah, I see.

03:39.067 --> 03:40.535
I understand why.

03:41.569 --> 03:43.772
No, to us it'd make
a huge difference.

03:45.273 --> 03:46.475
She'll be out soon.

03:47.875 --> 03:49.074
You had enough?

03:49.076 --> 03:51.514
<i>While most are rod shaped...</i>

03:53.648 --> 03:56.952
They want us on the boat
now for a team debriefing.

03:57.218 --> 03:59.020
Can I get
in the tank next time?

03:59.254 --> 04:00.223
That's dangerous.

04:00.421 --> 04:02.055
Each suit is designed
specifically

04:02.057 --> 04:02.992
for each aquanaut, so...

04:03.219 --> 04:05.327
Thank you, Paul, but you don't
have to indulge her every whim.

04:05.593 --> 04:06.995
Thank you, Paul.

04:08.563 --> 04:09.998
Why do you torture
him like that?

04:11.332 --> 04:13.068
He's too young
to defend himself.

04:18.106 --> 04:19.108
I'll race you.

04:19.940 --> 04:21.575
- No.
- Come on now.

04:21.577 --> 04:23.146
No, I... I...

04:24.947 --> 04:26.048
I don't like you!

04:28.183 --> 04:32.518
Okay, I just want to
go over the order of the dives,

04:32.520 --> 04:34.453
so that you can
communicate with each other

04:34.455 --> 04:35.924
about who can help log,

04:36.224 --> 04:39.162
as some of you will be prepping
and not available to log.

04:39.394 --> 04:40.296
All right?

04:40.462 --> 04:45.301
We start from here,
so Jonas and René are up first,

04:45.500 --> 04:47.534
- Lucky you.
- with Étienne as the pilot,

04:47.536 --> 04:49.839
for the first dive
in the Cadiz Gulf.

04:50.037 --> 04:53.006
Then we're going to
hug the coastline,

04:53.008 --> 04:56.075
going west of Ireland
and Britain

04:56.077 --> 04:57.679
into the Norwegian Sea.

04:58.212 --> 05:00.650
There, Gustavo and
Maria are next,

05:01.015 --> 05:04.953
with Frank piloting
around the Faroe Island.

05:05.453 --> 05:09.722
Frank, who is also taking
Annie and Mark down,

05:09.724 --> 05:14.029
here near Iceland where
we'll spend the most time,

05:14.229 --> 05:16.328
and do several dives, okay?

05:16.330 --> 05:17.797
It's a complete reversal,
I'm sorry.

05:17.799 --> 05:19.698
And then, our deepest dive,

05:19.700 --> 05:23.806
Thumbs and Dani,
are last, around Jan Mayen,

05:24.171 --> 05:26.508
with Étienne as a pilot, okay?

05:33.614 --> 05:36.618
There are definite
advantages in going last.

05:37.719 --> 05:40.490
They're gonna be logging
and not prepping,

05:41.423 --> 05:42.992
and the sub will be tested.

05:43.592 --> 05:45.260
I'm not thinking about that.

05:46.128 --> 05:47.630
Then what's up?

05:48.664 --> 05:50.967
I realized I've never
been lonely before.

05:55.137 --> 05:57.039
Welcome to the planet.

05:59.741 --> 06:01.840
It's possible there's
no service where he is.

06:01.842 --> 06:03.979
He's working in
Northern Kenya, right?

06:04.546 --> 06:06.182
Or he just stopped calling,

06:07.849 --> 06:09.381
stopped being interested.

06:09.383 --> 06:10.452
Impossible.

06:10.719 --> 06:12.518
He's just stuck somewhere
without reception.

06:12.520 --> 06:13.755
For a month.

06:14.155 --> 06:15.156
Yes.

06:16.024 --> 06:17.159
Why not?

06:51.292 --> 06:53.728
Don't go near him, boy!

08:41.434 --> 08:42.671
Next.

08:43.538 --> 08:46.375
<i>The Monk by the Sea is not...</i>

08:55.750 --> 08:58.386
<i>...The Berlin Academy
exhibition of 1810.</i>

09:07.763 --> 09:08.998
What do you got for us?

09:10.799 --> 09:12.498
I have a bona fide source,

09:12.500 --> 09:15.270
willing to give up an
operational bomb unit in Europe.

09:16.538 --> 09:17.870
They want to hit train stations.

09:17.872 --> 09:18.937
Where's the link?

09:18.939 --> 09:20.540
In Southern Somalia.

09:20.542 --> 09:21.874
What's on the
table for the source?

09:21.876 --> 09:23.710
British passport,
we want him.

09:23.712 --> 09:25.110
We found him,
we'll get him.

09:25.112 --> 09:26.779
He's my source,
so I'm going in alone.

09:26.781 --> 09:28.748
Somalia is not a good idea, J.

09:28.750 --> 09:30.052
I know.

09:30.684 --> 09:31.886
Check this out.

09:42.063 --> 09:44.766
We are talking about
bombs all over Europe.

09:45.033 --> 09:48.368
<i>If there's even a chance we can get out
in front of that, we have to take it.</i>

09:48.370 --> 09:50.405
We don't know who they are,
where they are.

09:51.005 --> 09:52.906
Their whole pipeline
of intelligence

09:52.908 --> 09:54.810
and soldiers waiting
to stream in.

09:55.177 --> 09:58.080
You don't even know what faction
is in charge in Kismayo right now.

09:58.313 --> 10:01.250
Well, I was hoping you could help
me out with who's in charge there.

10:02.683 --> 10:06.054
Oh, come on, James,
this isn't Afghanistan.

10:06.688 --> 10:08.223
<i>So, how are you getting in?</i>

10:08.756 --> 10:10.159
Small plane.

10:10.925 --> 10:13.395
I'll use my water
engineer alias.

10:15.197 --> 10:17.466
I'll meet my contact
at Kismayo airport.

10:17.665 --> 10:21.069
So, you're mister water expert
and you're gonna dig up some wells?

10:23.471 --> 10:26.004
<i>In the tooth again,
that's the safest.</i>

10:26.006 --> 10:28.240
Yeah, I'll activate it
once I'm there.

10:28.242 --> 10:29.377
Same as last time.

10:35.417 --> 10:37.419
Don't let them
know you speak Arabic, J.

10:37.619 --> 10:38.687
Guys, do me a favor,

10:38.953 --> 10:40.955
just tell me something
that's gonna help me, would you?

10:42.023 --> 10:43.092
Fuck.

10:47.962 --> 10:50.165
Yeah? Okay.

10:52.167 --> 10:54.466
<i>Wait, we've got
something for you.</i>

10:54.468 --> 10:55.503
<i>Look at the picture.</i>

10:56.871 --> 10:59.308
<i>You must remember this guy,
Yusef Mohamud al-Afghani.</i>

11:01.275 --> 11:02.377
Yeah.

11:03.645 --> 11:06.081
He was with Osama in 2001,
wasn't he?

11:06.313 --> 11:08.614
<i>Yeah,
apparently he's in Somalia now.</i>

11:08.616 --> 11:11.452
<i>We'll get you intel on him,
whatever we dig up.</i>

11:12.120 --> 11:15.524
<i>Give us a few days, J, we'll
contact you on a safe line.</i>

11:59.266 --> 12:00.365
Hey!

12:00.367 --> 12:03.371
Hi. You came yourself.

12:03.571 --> 12:05.975
For you,
Madame Flinders, of course.

12:07.509 --> 12:09.510
Oh, so good to be back.

14:03.357 --> 14:04.559
Evening.

14:04.925 --> 14:06.160
What kind of whiskey
do you have?

14:06.428 --> 14:08.027
I've got a good Japanese one.

14:08.029 --> 14:10.099
<i>Konnichiwa,</i> let's go Japanese.

14:13.201 --> 14:15.437
- You play rugby?
- I used to.

14:15.636 --> 14:17.573
- What's your name?
- Marcel.

14:17.938 --> 14:19.238
Why did you stop, Marcel?

14:19.240 --> 14:21.273
Oh, you know,
I just broke my neck.

14:21.275 --> 14:23.676
Stick that on room 12, please.

14:23.678 --> 14:25.179
- Okay.
- See you later.

14:36.757 --> 14:38.426
Your white wine, Madame.

14:39.693 --> 14:41.429
Thank you, Marcel.

15:18.533 --> 15:19.568
Hey.

15:20.834 --> 15:22.336
Good Morning.

15:26.174 --> 15:27.443
Good Morning.

15:28.076 --> 15:31.246
- You're English?
- British. Scottish British.

15:31.612 --> 15:33.912
Dani, Dani Flinders.

15:33.914 --> 15:35.284
James More.

15:37.684 --> 15:40.521
- Will I see you later?
- Yeah, I'd like that!

15:58.939 --> 16:00.275
Oh.

16:07.582 --> 16:09.617
I think you're following me.

16:12.486 --> 16:15.223
Or you're following
me in advance.

16:16.024 --> 16:17.926
Tricky.

16:18.358 --> 16:20.292
Mr. More,
the newspaper you wanted.

16:20.294 --> 16:21.796
Thank you, Beatrice.

16:25.900 --> 16:27.667
You're definitely following me.

16:27.669 --> 16:29.704
I haven't even had a
chance to shower yet.

16:29.904 --> 16:31.807
I love the smell of sweat.

16:34.375 --> 16:36.778
- I have to do some work.
- Is this your room?

16:37.946 --> 16:41.080
- Lunch?
- Would 1:30 be too late?

16:41.082 --> 16:42.351
No.

17:11.778 --> 17:13.678
<i>Free-living chemoautotrophic</i>

17:13.680 --> 17:15.982
<i>microorganisms at
hydrothermal vents.</i>

17:15.983 --> 17:20.618
<i>We integrated the analyses of IPL
diversity and delta13C values,</i>

17:20.621 --> 17:24.223
<i>delta13C lipid with
16S RNA gene-based...</i>

17:34.435 --> 17:36.171
Yes?

17:36.771 --> 17:38.473
<i>I've come
to take you to lunch.</i>

17:39.607 --> 17:40.939
It's open.

17:55.089 --> 17:56.592
Carry on, Professor.

17:58.258 --> 18:00.261
How did you know
I was a professor?

18:00.861 --> 18:03.564
I looked at your name on the
letter you picked up this morning.

18:07.101 --> 18:08.736
What are you a professor of?

18:09.903 --> 18:11.272
Take a guess.

18:13.006 --> 18:14.173
Um...

18:14.175 --> 18:15.777
Music?

18:16.009 --> 18:17.642
Nope.

18:17.644 --> 18:19.844
Do you mind turning
it down a little bit?

18:19.846 --> 18:21.082
It's awfully loud in here.

18:21.349 --> 18:23.882
I mean, you couldn't
really hear me...

18:23.884 --> 18:25.553
knock on the door even, so...

18:27.721 --> 18:30.791
- Thank you, Law?
- Please.

18:31.225 --> 18:33.762
- Uh, anthropology?
- Wrong again.

18:34.128 --> 18:35.961
Well, just... tell me then.

18:35.963 --> 18:38.800
I apply mathematics to the
study of life in the ocean.

18:39.199 --> 18:40.901
You're an oceanographer?

18:42.169 --> 18:44.505
There's no such
discipline as oceanography.

18:44.971 --> 18:46.705
I'm a bio-mathematician.

18:46.707 --> 18:50.344
It's the working of the science
to whatever is in the sea.

18:51.245 --> 18:52.781
Or at the bottom of it.

18:55.216 --> 18:56.651
Precisely.

18:58.753 --> 19:00.820
It's quite rude,
just sitting there, watching me.

19:00.822 --> 19:02.687
Insisting that
we eat something?

19:02.689 --> 19:04.525
I know, it's entirely
unreasonable.

19:07.661 --> 19:10.097
So, what ocean is your favorite?

19:10.430 --> 19:13.601
It has to be that one,
the Atlantic.

19:15.169 --> 19:16.571
Okay...

19:17.671 --> 19:18.640
Carry on.

19:18.906 --> 19:20.309
- About?
- The sea.

19:20.874 --> 19:23.377
I feel certain it's going
to tell me all about you.

19:28.216 --> 19:29.685
All right, then, um...

19:31.151 --> 19:33.051
close your eyes.

19:33.053 --> 19:35.721
You're determined not
to let me eat, aren't you?

19:35.723 --> 19:36.892
Close them.

19:41.161 --> 19:43.998
The ocean has five layers.

19:44.332 --> 19:47.332
- Five.
- Are you going to cooperate?

19:47.334 --> 19:48.367
Mm-hm.

19:48.369 --> 19:51.039
- I want you to picture this.
- Okay.

19:53.874 --> 19:59.747
Yes, it has five layers
and the first one is epipelagic.

20:00.948 --> 20:05.986
It contains all the plant
life and coral reefs.

20:07.688 --> 20:10.121
Whatever memory
you have of baptism,

20:10.123 --> 20:16.097
or any other form of submersion,
is there in the blue water.

20:17.331 --> 20:19.101
The next layer,

20:19.734 --> 20:21.803
is mesopelagic.

20:24.438 --> 20:26.608
This is the twilight zone...

20:27.742 --> 20:28.976
into which...

20:29.509 --> 20:33.814
blue and all other
colors and light vanish.

20:41.022 --> 20:44.159
Everything under the
mesopelagic is night.

20:44.592 --> 20:48.028
If you were with me
in a submersible,

20:49.429 --> 20:53.965
that's like
a deep-sea submarine...

20:53.967 --> 20:55.437
Is it yellow?

20:56.871 --> 20:58.707
- Of course it is.
- Excellent.

20:58.906 --> 21:00.705
If you were with me
in one of those,

21:00.707 --> 21:02.944
you would have spent
two hours at least,

21:03.578 --> 21:07.849
in the blackness you're
in now, to get down to...

21:12.186 --> 21:13.855
You can open your eyes.

21:14.956 --> 21:16.625
The hadopelagic,

21:17.358 --> 21:19.628
which is what interests me.

21:22.630 --> 21:27.065
Hadal from the Greek "Hades",
meaning unseen.

21:27.067 --> 21:28.569
Doesn't it mean hell?

21:31.005 --> 21:32.207
To some.

21:33.274 --> 21:37.379
This is the other world
in our world.

21:37.844 --> 21:39.978
It's just miles and
miles of blackness?

21:39.980 --> 21:41.982
No one knows much
about the mantle.

21:42.350 --> 21:43.749
They think it has no life,

21:43.751 --> 21:46.584
and therefore no
possibility of reanimation,

21:46.586 --> 21:48.956
and is so without
scientific interest.

21:49.990 --> 21:51.492
I disagree.

21:52.459 --> 21:53.826
It needs to be explored.

21:53.828 --> 21:57.232
What? Excuse me,
what exactly is it that you do?

21:57.430 --> 22:01.533
I... I study...
I collect samples,

22:01.535 --> 22:03.535
from what I think is...

22:03.537 --> 22:06.173
the living bit
of the mantle.

22:06.740 --> 22:10.878
The first few kilometers
underlying the Hadal deep.

22:11.445 --> 22:14.381
I believe that all life and...

22:14.649 --> 22:17.151
regeneration in our world
belongs to it.

22:17.985 --> 22:21.490
We refuse to value what's
down there because it's dark.

22:21.889 --> 22:25.092
We want to forget there
is darkness in our world, and...

22:26.593 --> 22:28.796
and to be on a beach
is to be lucky.

22:29.162 --> 22:31.665
We don't educate ourselves.

22:32.832 --> 22:34.433
Our world is
firstly about power,

22:34.435 --> 22:36.104
it's only secondly
about education.

22:50.317 --> 22:52.751
What?

22:52.753 --> 22:55.053
No, don't worry about me,
just you carry on.

22:55.055 --> 22:57.723
No, I'm just writing down
what you just said

22:57.725 --> 23:00.462
- about power and education.
- Mm-hmm.

23:00.727 --> 23:02.663
- Oh, wow, okay.
- I like it.

23:03.598 --> 23:07.569
I'm actually going down on one of those
submersibles in a couple of weeks.

23:07.767 --> 23:10.871
I've waited years
for this opportunity.

23:11.138 --> 23:13.842
Come on, congratulations.

23:15.575 --> 23:16.911
Thank you.

23:26.586 --> 23:28.355
What do you do?

23:28.855 --> 23:33.725
I consult on water
projects in Africa, actually.

23:33.727 --> 23:35.994
Hey, we've got water in common.

23:35.996 --> 23:39.601
- You work for charity?
- The British government.

23:40.333 --> 23:41.702
You live in Africa?

23:42.335 --> 23:43.637
Nairobi.

23:44.338 --> 23:45.571
Do you like it?

23:45.573 --> 23:47.309
I do, most of the time.

23:48.842 --> 23:50.943
Nairobi gets a bit
treacherous sometimes.

23:50.945 --> 23:52.781
People say it's like
an African river,

23:53.246 --> 23:54.480
you can't see into it,

23:54.482 --> 23:55.917
you don't know where
the crocodiles are,

23:56.117 --> 23:58.117
and you can't see the
rapids coming at you.

23:58.119 --> 24:01.590
But, I tell you,
it's got its own...

24:01.988 --> 24:03.091
luster.

24:04.025 --> 24:06.594
I kinda miss it,
when I'm away too long.

24:07.061 --> 24:07.996
Wonderful place.

24:09.729 --> 24:11.298
I have a pool.

24:15.035 --> 24:16.601
<i>So, you're saying that...</i>

24:16.603 --> 24:18.436
descending to
the bottom of the ocean,

24:18.438 --> 24:22.177
makes us challenge our sense
of self and where we came from?

24:22.642 --> 24:25.343
And that we are not
interested in your work,

24:25.345 --> 24:29.083
because we don't want to have
come from the scum in the ocean?

24:31.552 --> 24:33.321
It kind of makes sense to me.

24:35.156 --> 24:36.858
- Does it?
- Yeah.

24:37.591 --> 24:39.628
It's caused people
to fight over...

24:43.330 --> 24:45.400
When I drop everything...

24:46.233 --> 24:49.638
I wanna make a case for my
theory on life down there.

24:50.236 --> 24:53.807
And having been down there
it gets more complicated.

24:55.042 --> 24:59.246
What counts the most is
being published in <i>Nature.</i>

24:59.813 --> 25:01.515
So, you're going
to go down there

25:01.815 --> 25:03.884
and you're going to be
surrounded by water,

25:04.185 --> 25:08.323
and infinite blackness
in what, a month?

25:10.056 --> 25:10.857
Yeah.

25:11.124 --> 25:12.960
Are you afraid
something might happen?

25:14.894 --> 25:17.231
I try not to think about that.

25:19.365 --> 25:20.734
Why?

25:21.802 --> 25:23.138
What would happen?

25:24.438 --> 25:26.107
If the submersible
would crack?

25:26.306 --> 25:27.374
Mm-hmm.

25:28.842 --> 25:32.211
Water would come in and
my lungs would seal off,

25:32.213 --> 25:35.813
and I would die a dry drowning
by acidosis and hypoxia.

25:35.815 --> 25:37.384
What would that feel like?

25:47.428 --> 25:50.462
Well, if anything
were to happen,

25:50.464 --> 25:55.937
it would probably just be us
getting stuck down there,

25:56.669 --> 25:58.406
unable to move.

26:00.707 --> 26:04.709
And there's only five days
of oxygen in the sub,

26:04.711 --> 26:06.578
and no one can reach
you down there.

26:06.580 --> 26:07.682
Why?

26:07.684 --> 26:12.053
There's only one of those
deep sea submersibles in Europe.

26:15.755 --> 26:19.627
So, I wouldn't drown,
I'd suffocate.

26:20.393 --> 26:23.397
I'd have a lot of time
to think about things.

26:34.041 --> 26:36.144
What's that
tattoo on your arm?

26:36.442 --> 26:37.778
A mistake.

26:39.280 --> 26:42.083
- You were a paratrooper?
- Yeah, I was.

26:42.315 --> 26:45.919
I was very young, though. It was
just a short service commission.

26:47.121 --> 26:49.290
This is what
I wanted to show you.

26:55.028 --> 26:57.064
Now this is what
I came here for.

27:06.673 --> 27:08.709
There was 5,000
Canadian soldiers,

27:09.509 --> 27:12.446
and a thousand British soldiers
tried to take this beach.

27:14.380 --> 27:17.418
The guns inside that bunker
killed every one of them.

27:17.751 --> 27:19.287
It was an incredible sacrifice.

28:12.605 --> 28:14.342
Hey, hey, hey!

28:28.755 --> 28:30.057
Ah!

28:37.765 --> 28:38.867
Here.

28:39.934 --> 28:41.369
That was cold!

